{"award_age":57.0,"bio_image":"full\/58453dc2a43b7d0d08927d623b1c5fa12fbf5cc8.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1911-06-13T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1988-09-01T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/5\/5d\/Luis_Walter_Alvarez_1961.jpg\/240px-Luis_Walter_Alvarez_1961.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Luis_Walter_Alvarez","mini_bio":"<p><b>Luis Walter Alvarez<\/b> (June 13, 1911 \u2013 September 1, 1988) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Experimental_physicist\" title=\"Experimental physicist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">experimental physicist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Inventor\" title=\"Inventor\" class=\"mw-redirect\">inventor<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Professor\" title=\"Professor\">professor<\/a> who was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> in 1968. The <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/American_Journal_of_Physics\" title=\"American Journal of Physics\">American Journal of Physics<\/a> commented, \"Luis Alvarez was one of the most brilliant and productive experimental physicists of the twentieth century.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-AJP_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Luis_Walter_Alvarez#cite_note-AJP-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>After receiving his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/PhD\" title=\"PhD\" class=\"mw-redirect\">PhD<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> in 1936, Alvarez went to work for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Lawrence\" title=\"Ernest Lawrence\">Ernest Lawrence<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lawrence_Berkeley_National_Lab\" title=\"Lawrence Berkeley National Lab\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Radiation Laboratory<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_California,_Berkeley\" title=\"University of California, Berkeley\">University of California, Berkeley<\/a>. Alvarez devised a set of experiments to observe K-<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Electron_capture\" title=\"Electron capture\">electron capture<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Radioactivity\" title=\"Radioactivity\" class=\"mw-redirect\">radioactive nuclei<\/a>, predicted by the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Beta_decay\" title=\"Beta decay\">beta decay<\/a> theory but never observed. He produced <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Tritium\" title=\"Tritium\">tritium<\/a> using the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cyclotron\" title=\"Cyclotron\">cyclotron<\/a> and measured its lifetime. In collaboration with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Felix_Bloch\" title=\"Felix Bloch\">Felix Bloch<\/a>, he measured the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neutron_magnetic_moment\" title=\"Neutron magnetic moment\">magnetic moment of the neutron<\/a>.<\/p><p>In 1940 Alvarez joined the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/MIT_Radiation_Laboratory\" title=\"MIT Radiation Laboratory\" class=\"mw-redirect\">MIT Radiation Laboratory<\/a>, where he contributed to a number of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Radar\" title=\"Radar\">radar<\/a> projects, from early improvements to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Identification_Friend_or_Foe\" title=\"Identification Friend or Foe\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Identification Friend or Foe<\/a> (IFF) radar beacons, now called <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Transponders\" title=\"Transponders\" class=\"mw-redirect\">transponders<\/a>, to a system known as VIXEN for preventing enemy submarines from realizing that they had been found by the new airborne microwave radars. The radar system for which Alvarez is best known and which has played a major role in aviation, most particularly in the post war <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Berlin_airlift\" title=\"Berlin airlift\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Berlin airlift<\/a>, was <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ground_Controlled_Approach\" title=\"Ground Controlled Approach\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Ground Controlled Approach<\/a> (GCA). Alvarez spent a few months at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> working on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nuclear_reactor\" title=\"Nuclear reactor\">nuclear reactors<\/a> for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enrico_Fermi\" title=\"Enrico Fermi\">Enrico Fermi<\/a> before coming to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory\" title=\"Los Alamos National Laboratory\">Los Alamos<\/a> to work for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Robert_Oppenheimer\" title=\"Robert Oppenheimer\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Robert Oppenheimer<\/a> on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Manhattan_project\" title=\"Manhattan project\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Manhattan project<\/a>. Alvarez worked on the design of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Explosive_lens\" title=\"Explosive lens\">explosive lenses<\/a>, and the development of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Exploding-bridgewire_detonator\" title=\"Exploding-bridgewire detonator\">exploding-bridgewire detonators<\/a>. As a member of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Project_Alberta\" title=\"Project Alberta\">Project Alberta<\/a>, he observed the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Trinity_(nuclear_test)\" title=\"Trinity (nuclear test)\">Trinity nuclear test<\/a> from a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/B-29_Superfortress\" title=\"B-29 Superfortress\" class=\"mw-redirect\">B-29 Superfortress<\/a>, and later the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_bombing_of_Hiroshima_and_Nagasaki\" title=\"Atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki\" class=\"mw-redirect\">bombing of Hiroshima<\/a> from the B-29 <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Great_Artiste\" title=\"The Great Artiste\">The Great Artiste<\/a><\/i>.<\/p><p>After the war Alvarez was involved in the design of a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Liquid_hydrogen\" title=\"Liquid hydrogen\">liquid hydrogen<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bubble_chamber\" title=\"Bubble chamber\">bubble chamber<\/a> that allowed his team to take millions of photographs of particle interactions, develop complex computer systems to measure and analyze these interactions, and discover entire families of new particles and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Resonance_(particle_physics)\" title=\"Resonance (particle physics)\">resonance states<\/a>. This work resulted in his being awarded the Nobel Prize in 1968. He was involved in a project to x-ray the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Egyptian_pyramids\" title=\"Egyptian pyramids\">Egyptian pyramids<\/a> to search for unknown chambers. With his son, geologist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Walter_Alvarez\" title=\"Walter Alvarez\">Walter Alvarez<\/a>, he developed the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alvarez_hypothesis\" title=\"Alvarez hypothesis\">Alvarez hypothesis<\/a> which proposes that the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cretaceous%E2%80%93Paleogene_extinction_event\" title=\"Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event\">extinction event<\/a> that wiped out the dinosaurs was the result of an asteroid impact.<\/p><p>Alvarez was a member of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/JASON_(advisory_group)\" title=\"JASON (advisory group)\">JASON Defense Advisory Group<\/a>, the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bohemian_Club\" title=\"Bohemian Club\">Bohemian Club<\/a>, and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Republican_Party_(United_States)\" title=\"Republican Party (United States)\">Republican Party<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-harv_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Luis_Walter_Alvarez#cite_note-harv-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Luis Alvarez","place_of_birth":"San Francisco, California ,  USA","place_of_death":"Berkeley, California","text":"Luis Alvarez , Physics, 1968","year":1968.0}